      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Return Run with Walk Breaks\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with 3 minutes of brisk walking to warm up the foot and ankle. Pay attention to any stiffness — this is normal and should ease within the first few minutes.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run easy at 5:58/km. If any foot discomfort arises, immediately switch to a walk until it settles, then resume running. This is a run/walk session — there is no pressure to run the full 14 minutes continuously.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk the final 3 minutes. Gentle calf and plantar fascia stretches after — hold each for 30 seconds, no bouncing.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 minutes of brisk walking before you begin running. Roll your foot gently on a massage ball or water bottle for 60 seconds before heading out if your foot feels stiff in the morning.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes to finish. Stretch calves (both straight-leg and bent-knee versions) and gently stretch the plantar fascia by pulling your toes back. Ice the foot for 10 minutes if there is any residual soreness.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"James, this is your first run of the week and the goal is simple: accumulate easy time on your feet without aggravating the plantar fascia. Your recent runs have been going well — no pain on March 17th and only brief stiffness on March 10th that resolved quickly. That's a really encouraging pattern. Your physiotherapist has cleared you for 20 minutes easy only, so we're staying firmly within that boundary. The pace target is 5:58/km — the conservative end of your easy range — because the goal right now is tissue tolerance, not fitness. Walk breaks are not a step backward; they are a smart tool for managing load on healing tissue.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Midweek Easy Run — Consistency Builder\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 minutes walking. Notice how the foot feels compared to Tuesday — any changes in stiffness or soreness are useful information to track.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy continuous running at 5:58/km. If Tuesday went well with no foot pain, aim for slightly more continuous running today. If there was any discomfort Tuesday, use a 4-minute run / 1-minute walk pattern throughout.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes. Repeat your post-run stretching routine from Tuesday.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 minutes walking. If your foot feels stiff first thing in the morning, do your plantar fascia stretches before you even get out of bed — pull your toes back gently for 10 reps before standing.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes. Calf stretches and plantar fascia stretch. Ice if needed. This is also a good day to check in with yourself: how does the foot feel compared to the start of the week?\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This midweek run is about building consistency — the most underrated ingredient in a return-to-running plan. Three runs per week at easy effort, even short ones, does more for rebuilding your aerobic base and tissue resilience than two harder runs would. You've shown real discipline in keeping the pace honest at 5:58/km across your recent sessions, and that's exactly the right approach. The plantar fascia responds well to gradual, consistent loading — it's the spikes in load that tend to cause setbacks. We're deliberately keeping volume flat this week to let your foot consolidate the progress from last week's 9.7 km total.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Saturday Easy Long Run — Time on Feet\",\"target_distance_km\":5,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes. This is your longest run of the week — take the warmup seriously. Let the foot wake up gradually.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy running at 5:58/km. This is your 'long run' for the week — but at this stage of return, it is the same duration as your other runs. The distinction matters psychologically: treat Saturday as your anchor run, the one you protect most. Use walk breaks freely if needed.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes. Take a few extra minutes to stretch today — you have more time on the weekend. Calves, hip flexors, and plantar fascia.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 minutes walking. On Saturday mornings, the foot may feel stiffer after a night's rest — this is very common with plantar fasciitis. Do your toe-pull stretches in bed before standing, and take the first few minutes of the walk warmup slowly.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk at least 3 minutes. Full stretch routine today: calves (straight and bent knee), plantar fascia, hip flexors, and hamstrings. Ice the foot for 10 minutes if there is any soreness. Rest Sunday — this is intentional recovery, not lost fitness.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is your long run day, and we're honoring that preference even though the duration matches your other runs right now. Here's the physiological rationale: at this stage of return, the goal is not distance — it's consistent, pain-free loading. Your plantar fascia is a connective tissue structure, and connective tissue adapts more slowly than muscle or cardiovascular fitness. Your aerobic engine (VDOT 46.5 from your 44:00 10K) is still largely intact — what we're rebuilding is tissue tolerance and structural confidence. Once your physiotherapist clears you for longer durations and eventually speed work, your fitness will come back faster than you might expect. Sunday is a full rest day. Rest is not the absence of training — it is when adaptation happens. You've done the work; Sunday is when your body processes it.\",\"perceived_effort\":3}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
